Basically in programming language to repeat 1 task for a particular time sometimes infinite (Ram exhusted)
The for loop has a specific structure with three parts inside its parentheses, separated by semicolons:
for (initialization; condition; final-expression) { … }

• Initialization: This runs only once at the very beginning. It’s where you create your counter variable (traditionally named i for “index”).

• Condition: This is checked before each repetition. If the condition is true, the code inside the loop runs. If it becomes false, the loop stops.

• Final-Expression: This runs after each repetition. It’s where you usually increment your counter.
